  "prompt": "Why was the wax museum in Philadelphia built?",
  "response": "The wax museum in Philadelphia, known as the \"Philadelphia Tussauds,\" was built to serve as an educational and entertainment venue, similar to other Madame Tussauds wax museums around the world. These museums are typically designed to showcase lifelike wax figures of historical figures, celebrities, and cultural icons, providing visitors with the opportunity to learn about and engage with a wide array of personalities in an interactive and immersive setting. Wax museums often aim to attract tourists and locals alike by offering unique photo opportunities and creating a space where history, culture, and contemporary life intersect. While there are many reasons a city might develop such a museum, these typically revolve around cultural enrichment, tourism, and entertainment. It's important to verify whether there is currently an operating wax museum in Philadelphia, as such details can change over time.",
